                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="424967" author="pjones" created="Sat, 17 Aug 2024 13:04:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;IIUC, ok to re-close the ticket&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="424125" author="adilger" created="Sat, 10 Aug 2024 07:58:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think I&apos;ve changed my mind about this.  It makes sense that the root project quota enforcement is not done for files owned by root and with projid = 0, so I think your patch is OK, and in fact desirable to implement, so that root is not prevented from writing to internal files.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="424119" author="bzzz" created="Sat, 10 Aug 2024 04:22:36 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not sure exactly what scenario you are thinking about, so I will guess.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;llog files where we save unlinks are owned by root, so I guess an unlink from an ordinary user can will be able to fail if that llog file can&apos;t be appended due to root&apos;s limit?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="424109" author="adilger" created="Fri, 9 Aug 2024 23:39:42 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;@Andreas, so an ordinary user won&apos;t be able to remove own files and free space if root has consumed his quota?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not sure exactly what scenario you are thinking about, so I will guess.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think it would ever be the case that removing files would fail because of quota limits.  Possibly if there was a quota limit on projid=0 and ldiskfs didn&apos;t explicitly exclude that ID, but I don&apos;t think this will happen in practice.  In the deployments that I&apos;m aware of, the projid quota limit is only applied to non-zero projid.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That said, I don&apos;t think it is a great idea to enforce quota limits on the root user, but some sites have strange configurations and we can&apos;t prevent them from doing such things if they really want to.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="424045" author="bzzz" created="Fri, 9 Aug 2024 16:11:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@Andreas, so an ordinary user won&apos;t be able to remove own files and free space if root has consumed his quota?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
